Title:
Operating System Design Review: A systematic analysis of modern systems architecture

Type:
Documentation (GitHub repository / long-form research write-up)

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This repository is a large research write-up comparing modern OS user-mode architecture, centered on loaders/linkers and concurrency, with deep reverse engineering of the Windows loader (NTDLL) and comparisons to glibc/ELF and some macOS behavior.  
- It documents Windows “parallel loader” internals (work queues, loader worker threads, events, locks) and module lifetime state transitions (LDR_DDAG_STATE), with traces, WinDbg workflows, and supporting code/data.  
- A major theme is how Windows’ DLL ecosystem (circular dependencies, delay/lazy loading, DLL search order) and loader-lock semantics create correctness, deadlock, and security liabilities (e.g., DllMain constraints, destructor ordering hazards, timing windows).  
- It also argues that Windows thread lifecycle practices (process exit via NtTerminateProcess, DLL thread notifications, TLS/FLS patterns) lead to unsafe teardown behavior (“process meltdown”) and hard-to-reason-about shutdown states.  
- Useful for reverse engineers, Windows internals researchers, exploit developers, and defenders who need to understand loader behavior, module initialization edge cases, and where architectural quirks create attack surface or reliability issues.  
- Interesting because it combines practical reversing artifacts (traces, pseudocode, experiments) with cross-OS design comparisons and concrete failure modes tied to real Windows primitives.

Technical Focus:
- Windows loader internals (NTDLL Ldrp* functions, parallel loading, loader locks/events)
- Module dependency graphs and state machines (LDR_DDAG_NODE / LDR_DDAG_STATE)
- DLL initialization/finalization semantics (DllMain, constructors/destructors, TLS/FLS callbacks)
- Delay loading / lazy loading mechanics and failure modes
- Thread lifecycle and process teardown behavior (RtlExitUserProcess, NtTerminateProcess)
- Cross-OS loader/linker comparison (PE vs ELF, LoadLibrary vs dlopen, symbol resolution)

Use Cases:
- Reverse engineer Windows loader behavior for reliability/security research
- Identify deadlock-prone patterns involving loader lock, COM apartments, and DllMain
- Analyze DLL load/unload ordering bugs and lazy-load side effects in complex apps
- Build or validate loader emulation/compat layers (Wine/ReactOS gaps, parallel loading)
- Develop detections/hardening guidance around DLL search order and load-time injection risks
- Support exploit research involving module loading timing, IAT patch windows, and teardown races

Keywords:
Windows loader, NTDLL, LdrpQueueWork, LdrpWorkQueue, LdrpWorkQueueLock, LdrpLoadCompleteEvent, LdrpWorkCompleteEvent, LdrpProcessWork, LDR_DDAG_NODE, LDR_DDAG_STATE, PEB, TEB, loader lock, DllMain, DLL_PROCESS_ATTACH, DLL_PROCESS_DETACH, delay load, lazy loading, LoadLibrary, GetProcAddress, GetModuleHandle, dlopen, dlsym, glibc loader, ELF, TLS, FLS, COM, NtTerminateProcess, RtlExitUserProcess, DLL hijacking, WinSxS, activation contexts